04353nam a22006735i 9780226376806DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263768067 a10.7208/97802263768062doi  a(DE-B1597)524970  a(OCoLC)957521292  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBL65.S8bH69 2017 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a322.109732231 aHowe, Nicolas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLandscapes of the Secular :bLaw, Religion, and American Sacred Space /cNicolas Howe. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b8 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Landscapes of Secular Law -- t2. Church, State, and the Tyranny of Feelings -- t3. Performing the Constitutional Landscape -- t4. The Spiritual Gaze -- t5. Sanctity, If You Will -- t6. Looking Askance at the Sacred -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"What does it mean to see the American landscape in a secular way?" asks Nicolas Howe at the outset of this innovative, ambitious, and wide-ranging book. It's a surprising question because of what it implies: we usually aren't seeing American landscapes through a non-religious lens, but rather as inflected by complicated, little-examined concepts of the sacred. Fusing geography, legal scholarship, and religion in a potent analysis, Howe shows how seemingly routine questions about how to look at a sunrise or a plateau or how to assess what a mountain is both physically and ideologically, lead to complex arguments about the nature of religious experience and its implications for our lives as citizens. In American society-nominally secular but committed to permitting a diversity of religious beliefs and expressions-such questions become all the more fraught and can lead to difficult, often unsatisfying compromises regarding how to interpret and inhabit our public lands and spaces. A serious commitment to secularism, Howe shows, forces us to confront the profound challenges of true religious diversity in ways that often will have their ultimate expression in our built environment. This provocative exploration of some of the fundamental aspects of American life will help us see the land, law, and society anew.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aChurch and statezUnited States. 0aCultural landscapeszUnited States. 0aEnvironmentalismxReligious aspects. 0aLandscapesxReligious aspects. 0aReligion and lawzUnited States. 0aReligion and statezUnited States. 0aSecularismzUnited States. 4aenvironment. 4ageography. 4alandscape. 4alaw. 4asecularity. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226376806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226376806.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles